    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>Wet snow requires caution.</highlights>
      <comment>As a consequence of new snow and wind, wind slabs formed in the last few days at high altitudes and in high Alpine regions. &lt;br/> As a consequence of warming there will be a gradual increase in the avalanche danger. On very steep slopes the moist avalanches can be released naturally and reach medium size in isolated cases. &lt;br/> Individual avalanche prone locations are to be found on very steep shady slopes above approximately 2600 m. Avalanches can be released, mostly by large loads and reach medium size.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>Below approximately 2500 m a little snow is lying. The spring-like weather conditions will give rise to rapid moistening of the snowpack. The surface of the snowpack will only just freeze and will soften quickly. &lt;br/> Steep west, north and east facing slopes above approximately 2500 m: Faceted weak layers exist in the bottom section of the old snowpack.</comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
    <travelAdvisory/>
    <tendency>
      <highlights>The avalanche danger will persist.</highlights>
      <tendencyType>steady</tendencyType>
      <validTime>
